<h2>The Most Irrational</h2>=20

<p>I believe the Golden Ratio is the <b>most</b> <a href=3D"https://www.mat=
hsisfun.com/irrational-numbers.html">irrational number</a>. Here is why ...=
</p>

	<table style=3D"border: 0; margin:auto;">
		<tbody><tr>
			<td>We saw before that the Golden Ratio can be defined in terms of itsel=
f,<br>
like this:</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td class=3D"center larger">=CF=86 <em>=3D</em> 1 + <span class=3D"intbl=
"><em>1</em><strong>=CF=86</strong></span></td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td><i>(In numbers: 1,61803... <em>=3D</em> 1 + 1/1,61803...)</i></td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>&nbsp;</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>That can be expanded into this fraction that goes on for ever<br>
(called a <i>"continued fraction"</i>):</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td class=3D"center larger"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/numbe=
rs/images/phi-continued-fraction.svg" alt=3D"phi continued fraction: phi =
=3D 1+1/(1+1/(1+1/(1+1/..." height=3D"76" width=3D"199"></td>
		</tr>
	</tbody></table><br>

<p class=3D"center large">So, it neatly slips in between simple fractions.<=
/p>=20
<p>Note: many other irrational numbers are close to rational numbers, such =
as <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/numbers/pi.html">Pi</a> <em>=3D</e=
m> 3,14159265... is pretty close to 22/7 <em>=3D</em> 3,1428571...)</p>=20
<div class=3D"gap"></div>
<p class=3D"floatLt"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/geometry/images=
/pentagram-lengths.svg" alt=3D"pentagram lengths" height=3D"275" width=3D"2=
20"></p>=20


<h2>Pentagram</h2>=20

<p>No, not witchcraft! The pentagram is more famous as a magical or holy sy=
mbol. And it has the Golden Ratio in it:</p>=20
<ul>=20
	<li>a/b <em>=3D</em> 1,618...</li>=20
	<li>b/c <em>=3D</em> 1,618...</li>=20
	<li>c/d <em>=3D</em> 1,618...</li>=20
</ul>=20
<p>Read more at <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/geometry/pentagram.ht=
ml">Pentagram</a>.</p>=20


<h2>Other Names</h2>=20

<p>The Golden Ratio is also sometimes called the <b>golden section</b>, <b>=
golden mean</b>, <b>golden number</b>, <b>divine proportion</b>, <b>divine =
section</b> and <b>golden proportion</b>.</p>=20


<h2>Footnotes for the Keen</h2>=20

<div class=3D"def">=20

<h3>* Where did =E2=88=9A5/2 come from?</h3>=20

<p class=3D"floatRt"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/numbers/images/=
golden-ratio-r5-2.svg" alt=3D"golden ratio square root of 5 over 2" height=
=3D"221" width=3D"188"></p>=20
<p>With the help of <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/pythagoras.html">=
Pythagoras</a>:</p>=20
<p class=3D"so">c<sup>2</sup> <em>=3D</em> a<sup>2</sup> + b<sup>2</sup></p=
>=20
<p class=3D"so">c<sup>2</sup> <em>=3D</em> (<span class=3D"intbl"><em>1</em=
><strong>2</strong></span>)<sup>2</sup> + 1<sup>2</sup></p>=20
<p class=3D"so">c<sup>2</sup> <em>=3D</em> <span class=3D"intbl"><em>1</em>=
<strong>4</strong></span> + 1</p>=20
<p class=3D"so">c<sup>2</sup> <em>=3D</em> <span class=3D"intbl"><em>5</em>=
<strong>4</strong></span></p>=20
<p class=3D"so">c <em>=3D</em> =E2=88=9A(<span class=3D"intbl"><em>5</em><s=
trong>4</strong></span>)</p>=20
<p class=3D"so">c <em>=3D</em> <span class=3D"intbl"><em>=E2=88=9A5</em><st=
rong>2</strong></span></p>=20
</div>
<div class=3D"gap"></div>
<div class=3D"def">=20

<h3>Solving using the Quadratic Formula</h3>=20

<p>We can find the value of <span class=3D"golden">=CF=86</span> this way:<=
/p>=20
<div class=3D"two"> <span class=3D"lt">Start with:</span><span class=3D"rt"=
>=CF=86 <em>=3D</em> 1 + <span class=3D"intbl"><em>1</em><strong>=CF=86</st=
rong></span></span><span class=3D"lt">Multiply both sides by =CF=86:</span>=
<span class=3D"rt">=CF=86<sup>2</sup> <em>=3D</em> =CF=86 + 1</span><span c=
lass=3D"lt">Rearrange to:</span><span class=3D"rt">=CF=86<sup>2</sup> =E2=
=88=92 =CF=86 =E2=88=92 1 <em>=3D</em> 0</span></div>

<p>Which is a <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/quadratic-equat=
ion.html">Quadratic Equation</a> and we can use the Quadratic Formula:</p>=
=20
<p class=3D"center larger">=CF=86 <em>=3D</em> <span class=3D"intbl"> <em>=
=E2=88=92b =C2=B1 =E2=88=9A(b<sup>2 </sup>=E2=88=92 4ac)</em> <strong>2a</s=
trong></span></p>=20
<p>Using <b>a=3D1</b>, <b>b=3D=E2=88=921</b> and <b>c=3D=E2=88=921</b> we g=
et:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center larger">=CF=86 <em>=3D</em> <span class=3D"intbl"> <em>1=
 =C2=B1 =E2=88=9A(1+ 4)</em> <strong>2</strong></span></p>=20
<p>And the positive solution simplifies to:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center larger">=CF=86 <em>=3D</em> <span class=3D"intbl"><em>1<=
/em><strong>2</strong></span> + <span class=3D"intbl"><em>=E2=88=9A5</em><s=
trong>2</strong></span></p>=20
<p>Ta da!</p>=20
</div>=20

<div class=3D"gap"></div>
<div class=3D"def">=20

<h3>Kepler Triangle</h3>=20

<div class=3D"two"> <span class=3D"lt">We saw above that:</span><span class=
=3D"rt">=CF=86<sup>2</sup> <em>=3D</em> =CF=86 + 1</span><span class=3D"lt"=
>And Pythagoras says a right-angled triangle has:</span><span class=3D"rt">=
c<sup>2</sup> <em>=3D</em> a<sup>2</sup> + b<sup>2</sup></span></div>

<p>That inspired a man called Johannes Kepler to create this triangle:</p>=
=20
<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/numbers/images/k=
epler-triangle.svg" alt=3D"Kepler triangle" height=3D"354" width=3D"327"></=
p>=20
<p>It is really cool because:</p>=20
<ul>=20
	<li>it has Pythagoras and <span class=3D"golden">=CF=86</span> together</l=
i>=20
	<li>the ratio of the sides is <b class=3D"golden">1 : =E2=88=9A=CF=86 : =
=CF=86</b>, making a <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/sequence=
s-sums-geometric.html">Geometric Sequence</a></li>=20
</ul>=20
</div>=20

